      <hedline>
        <hl1>Hurricane Warning</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Paul Krugman Op-Ed column contends economic problems facing Argentina arise from anti-Keynesian hard-money policies, while recent turnaround in Brazil demonstates validity of Keynes' prescriptions for coping with recession (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A writer in Maryland (letter, June 1) labeled government disaster aid a ''national disgrace'' when provided to those who choose to live in ''fragile landscapes.''</p>
        <p>With the arrival of hurricane season, the Middle Atlantic states assume a fragility of their own. Surely the writer would not deny federal aid to any areas devastated if a tropical disturbance hits the Maryland shore and travels inland. And what about tornado damage in the Midwest?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A writer in Maryland (letter, June 1) labeled government disaster aid a ''national disgrace'' when provided to those who choose to live in ''fragile landscapes.''</p>
        <p>With the arrival of hurricane season, the Middle Atlantic states assume a fragility of their own. Surely the writer would not deny federal aid to any areas devastated if a tropical disturbance hits the Maryland shore and travels inland. And what about tornado damage in the Midwest?</p>
        <p>Every American landscape has its vulnerabilities. Each is worthy of our collective aid.</p>
        <p>MARK B. JACOBS  San Francisco, June 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
